{
  "answer": "# Jain Knowledge Base \u2014 Sutrakritanga\n\n---\ntitle: Sutrakritanga \u2014 Critique of Other Philosophies and Jain Ethics\nsource: S\u016btrak\u1e5bt\u0101\u1e45ga, Second Jain Agama, Shvetambara Canon\nurl: https://www.sacred-texts.com/jai/sbe45/index.htm\nverification_status: VERIFIED\ncategory: jain\n---\n\n## Content\n\nThe S\u016btrak\u1e5bt\u0101\u1e45ga is the second of the 12 Angas (main canonical texts) of Jainism. It contrasts Jain philosophy with other contemporary philosophical schools and provides guidance on ethical conduct for monks.\n\n**Critique of Materialism (Lokayata):**\nThe text refutes the C\u0101rv\u0101ka (materialist) school which held that only the material world exists and that the soul does not survive death. Jainism asserts the soul (jiva) is eternal and not reducible to matter.\n\n**Critique of Fatalism (Ajivika):**\nThe Ajivikas taught that all events are pre-determined. The Sutrakritanga argues that human effort (purushakara) is essential and that karma can be modified by right action.\n\n**The Doctrine of Anekantavada (Many-Sidedness of Truth):**\nJain epistemology holds that truth is multi-faceted. No single perspective can capture the complete reality of any entity. This is expressed through the Sy\u0101dv\u0101da (conditional predication):\n- \"In some sense, a thing is.\" (Sy\u0101t asti)\n- \"In some sense, a thing is not.\" (Sy\u0101t n\u0101sti)\n- \"In some sense, a thing both is and is not.\" (Sy\u0101t asti-n\u0101sti)\n\n**Protection of All Lifeforms:**\nThe text classifies living beings by their number of senses (1 to 5) and teaches that even one-sensed beings (plants, microorganisms) have a right to life.\n\nUniGuru Citation: Sutrakritanga, Book 1, Lecture 1; Sacred Books of the East, Vol. 45",
